==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*sweikan'': cognate with Old Frisian ''swīka'' ‘stay far from’, Old Saxon ''swīkan'' ‘betray, languish’ (Dutch [[bezwijken]] ‘give way, sink’), Old High German ''swīhhan'' (dialectical German [[schweichen]] ‘wander round, deceive’), Old Norse ''svíkva'' ‘betray’ (Swedish [[svika]], Danish [[svige]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'swi:kan/

===Verb===
'''swīcan''' (strong verb class I)
# to [[deceive]], be treacherous

